data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three Thread.Abort patterns that all need replacing:

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with rollback | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check; new CTS per item |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Per-item CTS linked to the parent — lets us cancel
            // one work item without tearing down the whole loop.
            using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token);      // see note on blocking calls below
                ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Shutdown requested — clean up and exit the loop.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Per-item cancellation (e.g., timeout on a single item).
                // Equivalent to the old ResetAbort path — loop continues.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // cooperative: signals the token

        // Give the thread time to finish its current item.
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after 2s, the thread is stuck in uncooperative code.
        // There is NO equivalent of Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
        // See "Uncooperative code" pitfall below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. Cancellation is now *cooperative* — your code must check the token voluntarily.

**2. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`**
The `when` filter distinguishes shutdown (parent token) from per-item cancellation (linked token), replacing the `ResetAbort` "keep going" pattern.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → linked `CancellationTokenSource`**
Instead of catching an abort and resetting it, create a per-item CTS. Cancelling it throws `OperationCanceledException` for that item only; the loop continues.

**4. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`**
The original code slept then rechecked. `Join` is cleaner — it blocks *at most* 2 seconds and returns immediately if the thread exits sooner.

## Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls

If `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take()`), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token:

```csharp
// ❌ Won't respond to cancellation — blocks forever
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ Throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
var item = queue.Take(token);
```

Every blocking or async call in the chain must accept and forward the `CancellationToken`. If even one method ignores it, cancellation stalls at that point.

## Other Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | What to do |
|---|---|
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using` or `Dispose()` — leaks timers/callbacks |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch at the top-level orchestration point; let it propagate elsewhere |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations |
| **Uncooperative code after timeout** | There is **no safe replacement** for `Thread.Abort` on stuck threads. If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that blocks forever, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort |
